The Strand-Out Insights:
Porosity is not just a trend—it's a behavioural shift
Consumers are beginning to treat porosity like a skin concern: something to diagnose, manage, and treat through multi-step regimes. This opens the door for Unilever to build deeper engagement through conditioning and styling routines that mirror skincare logic.
Porosity is emerging as a new way of talking about damage
It is reframing the conversation - moving beyond breakage, split ends and bonding to a more holistic, science-led and skincare inspired understanding of hair health.

BONUS FEATURE: AN INTERVIEW WITH OUR STYLIST TEAM
We spoke with Jess, Sarah and Kate—members of our stylist team with over 45 years of combined experience. Read to see how hair porosity shapes everything for stylists from product choice to styling longevity, and see why stylist expertise is essential to grooming our science in real-world hair experiences.
Please note, this is a view of porosity from a stylist's POV.
What is hair porosity?
"Porosity is how quickly hair absorbs and releases moisture. We see it most clearly with toners—porous hair grabs colour fast but loses it just as quickly."
What influences porosity?
"Heat damage, over-processing, and lack of protection. Textured hair tends to be naturally more porous than straight hair."
How do stylists test porosity?
"We do strand tests—pulling gently to check elasticity. If it stretches like chewing gum, it's porous and fragile. If it resists, it's stronger."
What do clients hear in consultations?
"We don't always say 'porosity'—we talk about dryness or damage. But we tailor advice to help build condition and protect the cuticle."
What are signs of Low vs High Porosity?
"Low porosity hair looks shiny and sleek, holds style well, and feels healthy. High porosity hair struggles to hold style, feels dry or brittle, and often shows signs of damage."
Does porosity affect product choice?
"We use Climazone to open cuticles with masks, then rinse with cool water to seal them. Porosity guides whether we use bond builders like Olaplex or K18"
Does porosity shape treatment decisions?
"Post-colour treatments like Wella's pH balancer help restore the hair. We always treat porous hair before colouring to prevent colour loss."
Anymore stylist insights?
"Porous hair grabs colour unevenly, especially at the ends. We adjust our approach—toners after bleach help even things out."

Activate With Purpose
Porosity & Styling (TRESemmé)
Tresemmé has the authority to reframe porosity as a pre-styling foundation and a styling-led, education-driven opportunity. Routed in salon expertise the brand can connect care, technology, and styling through a regime where wash and care lay the groundwork for enhanced and transformative styling outcomes.
PREP: Rebalance fibre porosity & infuse moisture to prime the hair
SEAL: Seal & resurface the hair during styling to shield the cuticle and lock in the infused moisture.
FINISH: Preserve the finish & extend the look for X days
Porosity & Curls (Sunsilk)
Sunsilk's brand essence has permission to activate porosity through a curl & waves lens. Porosity is a key challenge for curly hair—they lose moisture, frizz easily, and struggle to maintain their shape. Sunsilk can tap into the already established routine of improving porosity.
L - Liquid: Mist conditioners or water-based serums can be positioned as the first step to saturate and soften the fibre.
O - Oil: Position oils to seal the cuticle to prevent moisture loss and add shine & protection without greasiness.
C - Cream: Creams provide hold, definition, and long-lasting softness. Sunsilk's curl custards and butters can be framed as the final LOC step.
Porosity & Repair + Protect (Dove)
Porosity can be a sign of damage - lifted cuticles, dryness, dullness, breakage and even colour fade are all symptoms of porous hair. Dove has the scientific authority to educate and activate porosity through a 'repair & protect' first lens, focussing on improving porosity that has become porous with damage.
