From Trend to Tech | The R&D Response
Porosity may be trending in the outside world, but inside Hair R&D—we're testing it.
Whilst consumers are decoding their hair's moisture behaviour with float tests and TikTok videos, Hair R&D is decoding it with lasers, lipid chemistry, and diffusion coefficients.
Using the DSM instrument at MIF (image on the right), Hair R&D are measuring how hair fibres swell when immersed in water. By tracking the rate of this swelling, we can gain insight into how porous a hair fibre really is. Importantly, the rate of swelling gives us a way to quantify what consumers are already describing: how quickly their hair absorbs and loses moisture.
So, how do we improve it?
We've been putting hair through its paces: basewashes, hexane soaks, even chloroform-methanol cocktails (don't try this at home). The more we strip out lipids, the more porous the fibre becomes. But, once we bring those lipids back with a coconut oil emulsion, the fibre bounces back & porosity drops!
The people behind the science
Paul Carpenter and the MIF team are leading the porosity response, with support from our fibre and formulation experts. Together, they're turning porosity from a consumer curiosity into a measurable & claimable benefit for future products.

COMPETITOR LANDSCAPE
The porosity conversation is evolving... and our competitors are responding with precision.
L'Oréal is leading the charge with a multi-benefit strategy that spans metal detox, repair and colour variants. With each range tackling porosity from a different angle. No longer is porous hair just a technical detail, but it is now a consumer-facing claim platform. From Metal Detox's pre-shampoo filler to Vitamino's vibrancy lock, porosity is being positioned as the root cause of fade, frizz, and damage.
The messaging is clear: treat porosity, protect colour, preserve shine & strength.
Other brands such as Umberto Giannini, Cantu and CurlSmith are also exploring the high porosity space for textured hair.
For R&D and brand teams, the message is clear: porosity is no longer a technical or salon niche—it's a strategic claim space.
