Porosity Table
Low Porosity | Medium/'Optimal' Porosity | High Porosity
Presents As:

Low: Smooth, shiny, resistant to moisture; prone to build-up and long drying times
Medium: Balanced moisture, healthy shine, holds styles well
High: Frizzy, dry, tangles easily; absorbs fast but loses moisture quickly

Needs:

Low: Penetration support, lightweight hydration
Medium: Moisture-protein balance, routine maintenance
High: Rich hydration, sealing and resurfacing the cuticle

Treat:

Low: Clarifying shampoos, layer water-based leave-ins, humectant rich products (glycerin, aloe), sealing with light oils (jojoba, grapeseed), steaming
Medium: TikTok creators favour alternative deep treatments (moisture + protein), lightweight leave-ins, repair variants are often used to balance needs
High: Leave in products that claim to 'seal' hair fibres by adding a hydrophobic layer, reducing moisture loss and preventing frizz in humidity

Tools:

Low: Steamers, heat caps
Medium: Gentle detangling, traditional styling equipment
High: Low-heat stylers (e.g. Dyson Airwrap)

Based on online conversation

TREND STATS & SOCIAL MEDIA
Haircare that is reshaping routines
Hair porosity is having a moment—and it's not just a niche science term anymore. From TikTok tutorials to ingredient breakdowns, porosity is now a key lens through which Gen Z and Millennial consumers are decoding their hair needs. The hashtag #hairporosity has surpassed 79 million views on TikTok, whilst Google Trends shows 'Porosity' searches continues to increase from 2022. We're also seeing a rise of searches for porosity in relation to mask formats, with consumers owning the conversation on masks for low vs high porosity hair.
