Why now?
This trend is riding the wave of ingredient literacy, routine personalisation, and a growing demand for functional beauty. In a post-skinimalism era, consumers are asking not just what works, but why—and porosity offers answers. Whether it's clarifying for low porosity or sealing for high, creators are turning porosity into a diagnostic tool, not just a buzzword.
It's also deeply visual. From the viral "float test" as a measure of porosity, to ultra-satisfying product layering routines, porosity content taps into the same dopamine loop as heatless curls: education, transformation and reveal. And in a time where cost-of-living pressures meet high-performance expectations, porosity may be a way that consumers are looking to optimise without overspending.

WHAT IS POROSITY?
Porosity isn't a hair type - it's a hair behaviour
Hair porosity refers to how readily your hair retains and absorbs moisture. Some strands can have higher porosity, which makes them behave like a thirsty sponge. Whilst others can have lower porosity, which makes the fibre repel water like a raincoat. Porosity is governed by the structure of the hair cuticle—the overlapping cuticles that form the outer layer of each strand. These cuticles can be tightly sealed, slightly raised or wide open. Porosity is influenced by genetics... but it can also be influenced by chemical treatments, heat styling and environmental exposure - therefore, porosity isn't something that stays consistent over your life, it can change over time.
Lower Porosity Hair
Low porosity hair has cuticles that are tightly compact. It resists moisture & product penetration because of the tightly closed structure. Because of this, low porosity consumers will often say they have product build up or greasy hair and hairdressers describe it as 'resistant'.
Higher Porosity Hair
High porosity hair has lifted cuticles, allowing moisture and products to penetrate quickly, it also means that it loses them just as fast. Because of this, high porosity consumers will often say they have 'dry', 'rough hair'.

An Introduction
To understand where latest buzzword in the haircare world came from, we need to rewind back to a time when porosity wasn't a TikTok Hashtag...
Back in the 1990s and early 2000s, porosity wasn't part of consumer vocabulary. But hairdressers were taught the concept during training, and understood that how your hair absorbed and retained moisture could make or break a colour or a perm. They didn't always call it "porosity" to clients—instead, they'd say your hair was "dry", "damaged" and "resistant", and would use products to alleviate the problem prior to applying chemical treatments.
In fact, porosity was the unsung science behind one of the most iconic 90's films: Legally Blonde. When Elle Woods catches Chutney in a lie for showering right after a perm, she's actually invoking porosity logic. After a perm, hair can be highly porous—meaning if water is applied it can interfere with the newly formed bonds the perm has created.
The textured hair community—particularly consumers with Type 3 and 4 curls—played a pivotal role in bringing porosity into the spotlight. In the 2000s and 2010s, online forums, YouTube channels and blogs began to educate and share knowledge, especially on the nature of curly hair. Understanding whether hair was low, medium or high porosity became just as important as knowing your curl type. Now it wasn't just about how your hair looked, it was about how it behaves too.
Now in the 2020s, porosity is beginning to enter the mainstream. It's being talked about across all hair types online as consumers look for more personalised ways to understand their hair. And it's not just digital chatter: porosity is starting to show up on shelf too, with brands incorporating it into product claims, packaging, and even diagnostic tools. What was once a behind-the-scenes concept is now a front-of-pack feature.